JOHANNESBURG - Nearly 150,000 shares in the South African Reserve Bank are now available to purchase.The central bank says it wants to diversify its shareholder base.The decision follows a court order in November, directing those holding more than 10,000 shares, to sell the excess.READ: Apartheid reserve bank governor defends against Absa report allegationsShareholders will be allowed one vote to elect non-executive directors for every 200 shares held.Dividends are to be kept at a modest rate of 10c per share and bidding will be done via Investec and the Reserve Bank's website.The bank's ownership has come under scrutiny, with many questioning the role of private shareholders, in the running of the bank.SARB Shares Available to Members of the Public by eNCA.com on ScribdeNCA